posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: Has anyone else experienced an issue where the RoboRIO2 has ~100% CPU usage for right after you initially turn on your robot. The CPU utilization appears to be so high that, if you are quick to connect to the robot and then attempt to run the robot everything is non-responsive for 5-10 seconds. Then the CPU utilization drops to ~85% and the robot seems to run fine.

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked: The roborio needs to boot up right after you turn your robot on.  That includes loading the operating system, all the user code, etc.  It’s no different than your computer needing to load windows when you turn it on.

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked:
Yup, I get that.

By the time I am able to connect to the RIO via WIFI and enable I would have expected it to be up and running.

In previous seasons I don’t remember having this issue where the robot is “locked” up for 5+ seconds if we happen to enable soon after the robot is powered back on.

Maybe we are connecting earlier than we have in the past for some reason?

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: I don’t think we have tested rebooting the RoboRIO to verify it happens every time the RIO is booted. That is probably a good next step.

posts.name: Andrew McBride
posts.cooked: If the RIO is sitting consistently at >80% usage, I would definitely be considering how to reduce the CPU load. I would start at disabling the web server before moving into code and looking for optimization there.

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked:
Is disabling the web server a common thing?

It also seems weird to me that the CPU usage is that high. The only additional thread is the CTRE Swerve daq. Everything else should be pretty standard command based stuff.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
eddieD:

Is disabling the web server a common thing?

It’s starting to become common to free up RAM, it really shouldn’t use much if any CPU though.  We added a way to disable it in the WPILib 2024.2.1 RoboRIO team number setter tool.

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: Would anyone else besides @AndrewMcb be concerned about a constant 80% CPU usage?

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: Yes. You generally want to keep it lower.  I wouldnt do anything drastic like gut your code to get it from 81 to 79, but constantly >80 is generally indicative of you either trying to do too much, or something being done less efficiently than it could be.

posts.name: Sean Lynch
posts.cooked:
We are experiencing the same issue with the Robot being locked up for a few seconds after pushing code and enabling. The robot enables (flashing RSL ), but we can’t do anything. It’s weird because the RSL is flashing, but our LEDs are still showing that the Robot is in disabled periodic.

Additionally, we tried to disable the web service on our practice rio yesterday, but the option didn’t show up.  We are using a roborio v1 and WPILib 2024.3.1 and have the latest game tools. I will re-check that laptop tonight and try it on our comp rio.

Anyway - we started down the road of disabling the web service because we have been losing code while practicing with the following error which was stated to be a memory issue in another thread.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
slynch05:

we tried to disable the web service on our practice rio yesterday, but the option didn’t show up.

The desktop tools are only updated when you use the full installer, so most likely the tool is an older version.

We recently added documentation regarding memory debugging and system tuning that can be used.  Always start with using VisualVM to look at your memory allocations to see if there’s anything excessive, and then take tuning steps.

posts.name: Sean Lynch
posts.cooked:
Great, Thank you Peter!

Just a follow up on the note from Peter. We disabled the web server, set sysctls, and setup periodic GC and were able to run all night (~4 hours) without any memory errors where we would see 4-5 previously.
